    <section id="naming-history">
      <h2>The Name "Spring Festival" (<span class="chinese-char">春節</span>, <span class="pinyin">Chūnjié</span>)</h2>
      <div class="historical-note">
        <p>The name "Spring Festival" is surprisingly recent. For over a thousand years, the lunar new year was called <strong><span class="chinese-char">元旦</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">Yuándàn</span>, "first morning"). The earliest documented use appears in a poem by Xiao Ziyun (<span class="chinese-char">蕭子雲</span>, <span class="pinyin">Xiāo Zǐyún</span>) of the Liang Dynasty (502–557 CE): <em>"四氣新元旦，萬壽初今朝"</em> ("The four seasons begin anew at Yuandan, ten thousand years of longevity start this morning").</p>
      </div>
      <p>The name change came through two political acts in rapid succession:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>1912</strong> — Sun Yat-sen (<span class="chinese-char">孫中山</span>, <span class="pinyin">Sūn Zhōngshān</span>) proclaimed the Republic of China and adopted the Gregorian calendar. He reassigned the name <span class="chinese-char">元旦</span> (<span class="pinyin">Yuándàn</span>) to January 1st on the Gregorian calendar, leaving the lunar new year temporarily unnamed.</li>
        <li><strong>January 23, 1914</strong> — Yuan Shikai's Interior Minister Zhu Qiqian (<span class="chinese-char">朱啟鈐</span>, <span class="pinyin">Zhū Qǐqián</span>) formally proposed renaming the lunar new year as <span class="chinese-char">春節</span> (<span class="pinyin">Chūnjié</span>, "Spring Festival"). The proposal was approved, giving the celebration its modern name.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>In 1949, the People's Republic of China reconfirmed this arrangement. The term <span class="chinese-char">春節</span> (<span class="pinyin">Chūnjié</span>) is thus a 20th-century political creation — the celebration itself is ancient, but its current name dates only to 1914.</p>
      <div class="source-box">
        <p>Before 1914, the lunar new year was variously called <span class="chinese-char">元旦</span> (<span class="pinyin">Yuándàn</span>), <span class="chinese-char">歲首</span> (<span class="pinyin">Suìshǒu</span>, "year's head"), <span class="chinese-char">正旦</span> (<span class="pinyin">Zhèngdàn</span>, "first dawn"), or simply <span class="chinese-char">過年</span> (<span class="pinyin">Guònián</span>, "passing the year") — a colloquial term still universally used today.</p>
        <cite>— Historical note on pre-Republican naming conventions</cite>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="origins">
      <h2>Ancient Origins</h2>
      <p>The festival's roots lie in ancient year-end sacrificial rites (<span class="chinese-char">臘祭</span>, <span class="pinyin">làjì</span>) during the Shang Dynasty, when people offered sacrifices to ancestors and deities to give thanks for the harvest and pray for a prosperous new year. The word "Nian" (<span class="chinese-char">年</span>, <span class="pinyin">nián</span>) originally referred to the ripening of grain &mdash; a full harvest cycle.</p>
      <p>By the Zhou Dynasty, formalised celebrations at year's end included communal feasting and ritual offerings. Emperor Wu of Han's calendar reform in 104 BCE fixed the new year to the first day of the first lunar month, establishing the date that has endured for over two thousand years.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="nian-legend">
      <h2>The Nian Beast Myth — A Modern Invention</h2>

      <div class="callout-box callout-box--red">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div class="callout-content">
          <h3>Scholarly Correction</h3>
          <p>The "Nian beast" (<span class="chinese-char">年獸</span>, <span class="pinyin">Niánshòu</span>) story is a <strong>20th-century invention</strong>. No pre-Qing source mentions a beast called "Nian." The earliest known version is by Sun Yusheng (<span class="chinese-char">孫玉聲</span>, <span class="pinyin">Sūn Yùshēng</span>) in the Shanghai tabloid <em>《金剛鑽》</em> (<span class="pinyin">Jīngāngzuàn</span>) on <strong>January 17, 1933</strong>. The canonical version was amplified by a 1980 <em>《人民日報》</em> (<span class="pinyin">Rénmín Rìbào</span>) article and entered school textbooks.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="quote-card">
        <div class="quote-card-mark">"</div>
        <blockquote>年，穀熟也 — "Nian means the ripening of grain."</blockquote>
        <cite>— Xu Shen, <em>《說文解字》</em> (<span class="pinyin">Shuōwén Jiězì</span>) (c. 100 CE)</cite>
      </div>

      <p>The character <span class="chinese-char">年</span> (<span class="pinyin">nián</span>) referred to the annual agricultural harvest cycle, not a creature. The real origins of Spring Festival customs are better documented and far older than any beast myth.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="authentic-customs">
      <h2>Authentic Pre-Qing Origins of New Year Customs</h2>
      <p>The Spring Festival customs falsely attributed to the Nian beast each have their own distinct, well-documented histories:</p>

      <h3>Firecrackers (<span class="chinese-char">爆竹</span>, <span class="pinyin">Bàozhú</span>)</h3>
      <div class="source-box">
        <p>"正月一日……雞鳴而起，先於庭前爆竹，以辟山臊惡鬼。"</p>
        <p>"On the first day of the first month… rise at cockcrow, and set off bamboo crackers in the courtyard to drive away the mountain sprites and evil ghosts (<span class="chinese-char">山臊</span>/<span class="chinese-char">山魈</span>)."</p>
        <cite>— Zong Lin (<span class="chinese-char">宗懍</span>, <span class="pinyin">Zōng Lǐn</span>), <em>《荊楚歲時記》</em> (<span class="pinyin">Jīngchǔ Suìshí Jì</span>, Record of the Seasons of Jing and Chu), 6th century CE</cite>
      </div>
      <p>The original "firecrackers" were literally <strong>exploding bamboo</strong> — green bamboo stalks thrown into fires, which burst loudly as trapped air expanded. The practice targeted <span class="chinese-char">山臊</span> (<span class="pinyin">shānsāo</span>) or <span class="chinese-char">山魈</span> (<span class="pinyin">shānxiāo</span>), mountain spirits believed to cause illness — not any beast called "Nian." Gunpowder firecrackers appeared after the Tang Dynasty invention of black powder, eventually replacing bamboo.</p>

      <h3>Red Decorations — from Peachwood Charms (<span class="chinese-char">桃符</span>, <span class="pinyin">Táofú</span>)</h3>
      <p>Red decorations did not originate from a beast's fear. They evolved from <strong><span class="chinese-char">桃符</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">táofú</span>) — peachwood boards inscribed with the names of protective deities <strong><span class="chinese-char">神荼</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">Shéntú</span>) and <strong><span class="chinese-char">鬱壘</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">Yùlěi</span>), hung beside doors to repel evil. This practice is documented from the Han Dynasty. During the Five Dynasties (907–960 CE), auspicious couplets began replacing deity names. By the <strong>Ming Dynasty</strong>, peachwood was replaced by <strong>red paper</strong>, completing the evolution to the spring couplets (<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span>, <span class="pinyin">Chūnlián</span>) we recognise today.</p>

      <h3>Door Gods (<span class="chinese-char">門神</span>, <span class="pinyin">Ménshén</span>)</h3>
      <p>Door gods evolved through three stages:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Han Dynasty</strong> — <span class="chinese-char">桃符</span> (<span class="pinyin">Táofú</span>) boards with the names Shentu and Yulei carved on them</li>
        <li><strong>Sui–Tang period</strong> — Carved wooden deity figures replaced inscriptions</li>
        <li><strong>Tang Dynasty onward</strong> — Painted generals <strong>Qin Shubao</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">秦叔寶</span>, <span class="pinyin">Qín Shūbǎo</span>) and <strong>Yuchi Gong</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">尉遲恭</span>, <span class="pinyin">Yùchí Gōng</span>) became the dominant door god pair, based on a legend about Emperor Taizong's nightmares</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Spring Couplets (<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span>, <span class="pinyin">Chūnlián</span>)</h3>
      <p>The tradition of paired auspicious poetry on doorframes originated in the <strong>Five Dynasties period</strong> (907–960 CE). The earliest recorded spring couplet is attributed to Meng Chang (<span class="chinese-char">孟昶</span>, <span class="pinyin">Mèng Chǎng</span>), the last ruler of Later Shu: <em>"新年納餘慶，嘉節號長春"</em> ("In the new year receive lasting blessings; on this fine festival, hail enduring spring"). The practice moved from peachwood boards to red paper during the Ming Dynasty, when Emperor Taizu is said to have encouraged their widespread adoption.</p>

      <h3>Staying Up on New Year's Eve (<span class="chinese-char">守歲</span>, <span class="pinyin">Shǒusuì</span>)</h3>
      <p>The custom of staying awake through New Year's Eve is documented since the <strong>Jin Dynasty</strong> (265–420 CE). The poet Zhou Chu (<span class="chinese-char">周處</span>, <span class="pinyin">Zhōu Chǔ</span>) described the practice in <em>《風土記》</em> (<span class="pinyin">Fēngtǔ Jì</span>): families gathered, feasted, and stayed up together to "guard the year's passing." This had nothing to do with fearing a beast — it was an act of reverence for time, family unity, and the threshold between old and new.</p>
    </section>

